				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical model for a binary dependent variable</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Logit model=
" redirects here; not to be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Logit_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logit function">Logi=
t function</a>.</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Exam_pass_logistic_curve.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Exam_pass_logist=
ic_curve.svg/500px-Exam_pass_logistic_curve.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" wid=
th=3D"400" height=3D"277" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"609"=
 data-file-height=3D"421"></a><figcaption>Example graph of a logistic regre=
ssion curve fitted to data. The curve shows the estimated probability of pa=
ssing an exam (binary dependent variable) versus hours studying (scalar ind=
ependent variable). See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_r=
egression#Example">=C2=A7&nbsp;Example</a> for worked details.</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, a <b>logistic model</b> (or <b>logit model</b>) is a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model" title=3D"Statist=
ical model">statistical model</a> that models the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logit" title=3D"Logit">log-odds</a> of an event as a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_function_(calculus)" title=3D"Lin=
ear function (calculus)">linear combination</a> of one or more <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Independent variable">independent variables</a>. In <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" title=3D"Regression analysis"=
>regression analysis</a>, <b>logistic regression</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regre=
ssion#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (or <b>logit regression</b>) <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimation_theory" title=3D"Estimation theory">est=
imates</a> the parameters of a logistic model (the coefficients in the line=
ar or non linear combinations). In binary logistic regression there is a si=
ngle <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_variable" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Binary variable">binary</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Dependent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dependent v=
ariable">dependent variable</a>, coded by an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Indicator_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Indicator var=
iable">indicator variable</a>, where the two values are labeled "0" and "1"=
, while the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_variable" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent variable">independent variables<=
/a> can each be a binary variable (two classes, coded by an indicator varia=
ble) or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_variable" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Continuous variable">continuous variable</a> (a=
ny real value). The corresponding probability of the value labeled "1" can =
vary between 0 (certainly the value "0") and 1 (certainly the value "1"), h=
ence the labeling;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Hosmer-2"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> the function that converts log-odds to probability is the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function" title=3D"Logistic fu=
nction">logistic function</a>, hence the name. The <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" title=3D"Unit of measurement">unit of=
 measurement</a> for the log-odds scale is called a <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logit" title=3D"Logit">logit</a></i>, from <i><b>log</=
b>istic un<b>it</b></i>, hence the alternative names. See <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#Background">=C2=A7&nbsp;Backgro=
und</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#De=
finition">=C2=A7&nbsp;Definition</a> for formal mathematics, and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#Example">=C2=A7&nbsp;Exa=
mple</a> for a worked example.
</p><p>Binary variables are widely used in statistics to model the probabil=
ity of a certain class or event taking place, such as the probability of a =
team winning, of a patient being healthy, etc. (see <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#Applications">=C2=A7&nbsp;Application=
s</a>), and the logistic model has been the most commonly used model for <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_regression" title=3D"Binary r=
egression">binary regression</a> since about 1970.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTECramer200210=E2=80=9311_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer200210%E2%80%=
9311-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Binary variables can be generalized to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_variable" title=3D"Categorical variable=
">categorical variables</a> when there are more than two possible values (e=
.g. whether an image is of a cat, dog, lion, etc.), and the binary logistic=
 regression generalized to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multino=
mial_logistic_regression" title=3D"Multinomial logistic regression">multino=
mial logistic regression</a>. If the multiple categories are <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_of_measurement#Ordinal_scale" title=3D"Lev=
el of measurement">ordered</a>, one can use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ordinal_logistic_regression" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"O=
rdinal logistic regression">ordinal logistic regression</a> (for example th=
e proportional odds ordinal logistic model<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wal67est_4-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regr=
ession#cite_note-wal67est-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>). See <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#Extensions">=C2=A7&nbsp;Extensions</a> for =
further extensions. The logistic regression model itself simply models prob=
ability of output in terms of input and does not perform <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_classification" title=3D"Statistical cla=
ssification">statistical classification</a> (it is not a classifier), thoug=
h it can be used to make a classifier, for instance by choosing a cutoff va=
lue and classifying inputs with probability greater than the cutoff as one =
class, below the cutoff as the other; this is a common way to make a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_classifier" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Binary classifier">binary classifier</a>.
</p><p>Analogous linear models for binary variables with a different <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function" title=3D"Sigmoid funct=
ion">sigmoid function</a> instead of the logistic function (to convert the =
linear combination to a probability) can also be used, most notably the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probit_model" title=3D"Probit model">=
probit model</a>; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_reg=
ression#Alternatives">=C2=A7&nbsp;Alternatives</a>. The defining characteri=
stic of the logistic model is that increasing one of the independent variab=
les multiplicatively scales the odds of the given outcome at a <i>constant<=
/i> rate, with each independent variable having its own parameter; for a bi=
nary dependent variable this generalizes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Odds_ratio" title=3D"Odds ratio">odds ratio</a>. More abstractly=
, the logistic function is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nat=
ural_parameter" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Natural parameter">natural p=
arameter</a> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_dis=
tribution" title=3D"Bernoulli distribution">Bernoulli distribution</a>, and=
 in this sense is the "simplest" way to convert a real number to a probabil=
ity.
</p><p>The parameters of a logistic regression are most commonly estimated =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum-likelihood_estimation" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum-likelihood estimation">maximum-likel=
ihood estimation</a> (MLE). This does not have a closed-form expression, un=
like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_least_squares_(mathema=
tics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear least squares (mathematics)">l=
inear least squares</a>; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logis=
tic_regression#Model_fitting">=C2=A7&nbsp;Model fitting</a>. Logistic regre=
ssion by MLE plays a similarly basic role for binary or categorical respons=
es as linear regression by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinar=
y_least_squares" title=3D"Ordinary least squares">ordinary least squares</a=
> (OLS) plays for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Scalar (mathematics)">scalar</a> responses: it is a simple, =
well-analyzed baseline model; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Logistic_regression#Comparison_with_linear_regression">=C2=A7&nbsp;Comparis=
on with linear regression</a> for discussion. The logistic regression as a =
general statistical model was originally developed and popularized primaril=
y by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Berkson" title=3D"Jose=
ph Berkson">Joseph Berkson</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20028_5-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regr=
ession#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20028-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> beginning in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFBerkson1944">Berks=
on (1944)</a>, where he coined "logit"; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#History">=C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>.
</p>
