<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_reg=
ression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Applicati=
ons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"General">General</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: General"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Logistic regression is used in various fields, including machine learnin=
g, most medical fields, and social sciences. For example, the Trauma and In=
jury Severity Score (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRISS" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TRISS">TRISS</a>), which is widely used to predic=
t mortality in injured patients, was originally developed by Boyd <i><abbr =
title=3D"''et alia'', with others - usually other authors">et al.</abbr></i=
> using logistic regression.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-6"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>  Many other medical scales used to assess severity of a patient have =
been developed using logistic regression.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_=
note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regressio=
n#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Logistic regression may be used to predict the =
risk of developing a given disease (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Diabetes_mellitus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Diabetes mellitus"=
>diabetes</a>; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronary_artery_dis=
ease" title=3D"Coronary artery disease">coronary heart disease</a>), based =
on observed characteristics of the patient (age, sex, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_mass_index" title=3D"Body mass index">body mass in=
dex</a>, results of various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_=
test" title=3D"Blood test">blood tests</a>, etc.).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freed=
man09_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
gistic_regression#cite_note-Freedman09-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_re=
gression#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Another example might be to predict w=
hether a Nepalese voter will vote Nepali Congress or Communist Party of Nep=
al or for any other party, based on age, income, sex, race, state of reside=
nce, votes in previous elections, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rms_13-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression=
#cite_note-rms-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The technique can also be used in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engineeri=
ng</a>, especially for predicting the probability of failure of a given pro=
cess, system or product.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-strano05_14-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-=
strano05-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-safety_15-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-sa=
fety-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> It is also used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Marketing" title=3D"Marketing">marketing</a> applications such as pre=
diction of a customer's propensity to purchase a product or halt a subscrip=
tion, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics=
</a>, it can be used to predict the likelihood of a person ending up in the=
 labor force, and a business application would be to predict the likelihood=
 of a homeowner defaulting on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
rtgage" title=3D"Mortgage">mortgage</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Conditional_random_field" title=3D"Conditional random field">Conditi=
onal random fields</a>, an extension of logistic regression to sequential d=
ata, are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_=
processing" title=3D"Natural language processing">natural language processi=
ng</a>. Disaster planners and engineers  rely on these models to predict de=
cisions taken by householders or building occupants in small-scale and larg=
e-scales evacuations, such as building fires, wildfires, hurricanes among o=
thers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logi=
stic_regression#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite=
_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> These models help in the development of reliable <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergency_management" title=3D"Emergen=
cy management">disaster managing plans</a> and safer design for the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Built_environment" title=3D"Built environ=
ment">built environment</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Supervised_machine_learning=
">Supervised machine learning</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Supervised machine learning"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Logistic regression is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superv=
ised_machine_learning" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Supervised machine le=
arning">supervised machine learning</a> algorithm widely used for <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_classification" title=3D"Binary cl=
assification">binary classification</a> tasks, such as identifying whether =
an email is spam or not and diagnosing diseases by assessing the presence o=
r absence of specific conditions based on patient test results. This approa=
ch utilizes the logistic (or sigmoid) function to transform a linear combin=
ation of input features into a probability value ranging between 0 and 1. T=
his probability indicates the likelihood that a given input corresponds to =
one of two predefined categories. The essential mechanism of logistic regre=
ssion is grounded in the logistic function's ability to model the probabili=
ty of binary outcomes accurately. With its distinctive S-shaped curve, the =
logistic function effectively maps any real-valued number to a value within=
 the 0 to 1 interval. This feature renders it particularly suitable for bin=
ary classification tasks, such as sorting emails into "spam" or "not spam".=
 By calculating the probability that the dependent variable will be categor=
ized into a specific group, logistic regression provides a probabilistic fr=
amework that supports informed decision-making.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regressio=
n#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Example">Example</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Example"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Problem">Problem</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Problem"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As a simple example, we can use a logistic regression with one explanato=
ry variable and two categories to answer the following question:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>A group of 20 students spends between 0 and 6 hours studying for an exam=
. How does the number of hours spent studying affect the probability of the=
 student passing the exam?
</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The reason for using logistic regression for this problem is that the va=
lues of the dependent variable, pass and fail, while represented by "1" and=
 "0", are not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_number" tit=
le=3D"Cardinal number">cardinal numbers</a>. If the problem was changed so =
that pass/fail was replaced with the grade 0=E2=80=93100 (cardinal numbers)=
, then simple <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis"=
 title=3D"Regression analysis">regression analysis</a> could be used.
</p><p>The table shows the number of hours each student spent studying, and=
 whether they passed (1) or failed (0).
</p>
