neralizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>This simple model is an example of binary logistic regression, and has o=
ne explanatory variable and a binary categorical variable which can assume =
one of two categorical values. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mul=
tinomial_logistic_regression" title=3D"Multinomial logistic regression">Mul=
tinomial logistic regression</a> is the generalization of binary logistic r=
egression to include any number of explanatory variables and any number of =
categories.
</p>
