</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regress=
ion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Definition">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>A dataset contains <i>N</i> points. Each point <i>i</i> consists of a se=
t of <i>m</i> input variables <i>x</i><sub>1,<i>i</i></sub> ... <i>x</i><su=
b><i>m,i</i></sub> (also called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
dependent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent variable">in=
dependent variables</a>, explanatory variables, predictor variables, featur=
es, or attributes), and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_v=
ariable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary variable">binary</a> outcome=
 variable <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> (also known as a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dep=
endent variable">dependent variable</a>, response variable, output variable=
, or class), i.e. it can assume only the two possible values 0 (often meani=
ng "no" or "failure") or 1 (often meaning "yes" or "success"). The goal of =
logistic regression is to use the dataset to create a predictive model of t=
he outcome variable.
</p><p>As in linear regression, the outcome variables <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i>=
</sub> are assumed to depend on the explanatory variables <i>x</i><sub>1,<i=
>i</i></sub> ... <i>x</i><sub><i>m,i</i></sub>.
</p>
<dl><dt>Explanatory variables</dt></dl>
<p>The explanatory variables may be of any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Statistical_data_type" title=3D"Statistical data type">type</a>: <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-valued" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Real-valued">real-valued</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Binary_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary variable">binar=
y</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_variable" title=
=3D"Categorical variable">categorical</a>, etc.  The main distinction is be=
tween <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_variable" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Continuous variable">continuous variables</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_variable" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Discrete variable">discrete variables</a>.
</p><p>(Discrete variables referring to more than two possible choices are =
typically coded using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dummy_variab=
le_(statistics)" title=3D"Dummy variable (statistics)">dummy variables</a> =
(or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicator_variable" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Indicator variable">indicator variables</a>), that is,=
 separate explanatory variables taking the value 0 or 1 are created for eac=
h possible value of the discrete variable, with a 1 meaning "variable does =
have the given value" and a 0 meaning "variable does not have that value".)
</p>
<dl><dt>Outcome variables</dt></dl>
<p>Formally, the outcomes <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> are described as bein=
g <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_distribution" title=3D=
"Bernoulli distribution">Bernoulli-distributed</a> data, where each outcome=
 is determined by an unobserved probability <i>p</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> tha=
t is specific to the outcome at hand, but related to the explanatory variab=
les.  This can be expressed in any of the following equivalent forms:
</p>
