        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle y=3D1}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/10f53b404b1fdd041a589f1f2425e45a2edba110" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:5.416ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle y=
=3D1}"></span>. This linear relationship may be extended to the case of <i>=
M</i> explanatory variables:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e t=3D\log _{b}{\frac {p}{1-p}}=3D\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x_{1}+\beta _{2}x_{2=
}+\cdots +\beta _{M}x_{M}}">
