<p>This formulation expresses logistic regression as a type of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model" title=3D"Generalized=
 linear model">generalized linear model</a>, which predicts variables with =
various types of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distr=
ibution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distributions</a> b=
y fitting a linear predictor function of the above form to some sort of arb=
itrary transformation of the expected value of the variable.
</p><p>The intuition for transforming using the logit function (the natural=
 log of the odds) was explained above<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template"=
 style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please cla=
rify"><span title=3D"What exactly was explained? (February 2023)">clarifica=
tion needed</span></a></i>]</sup>.  It also has the practical effect of con=
verting the probability (which is bounded to be between 0 and 1) to a varia=
ble that ranges over <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inlin=
e"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"dis=
play: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"=
{\displaystyle (-\infty ,+\infty )}">
