of the linear prediction function on the right side of the equation.
</p><p>Both the probabilities <i>p</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> and the regressio=
n coefficients are unobserved, and the means of determining them is not par=
t of the model itself.  They are typically determined by some sort of optim=
ization procedure, e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_li=
kelihood_estimation" title=3D"Maximum likelihood estimation">maximum likeli=
hood estimation</a>, that finds values that best fit the observed data (i.e=
. that give the most accurate predictions for the data already observed), u=
sually subject to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regularization_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Regularization (mathematics)">regularization</a> con=
ditions that seek to exclude unlikely values, e.g. extremely large values f=
or any of the regression coefficients.  The use of a regularization conditi=
on is equivalent to doing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_=
a_posteriori" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum a posteriori">maximum =
a posteriori</a> (MAP) estimation, an extension of maximum likelihood.  (Re=
gularization is most commonly done using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ridge_regression" title=3D"Ridge regression">a squared regularizing =
function</a>, which is equivalent to placing a zero-mean <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Gaussian distribution">Gaussian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Prior_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prior distribution=
">prior distribution</a> on the coefficients, but other regularizers are al=
so possible.)  Whether or not regularization is used, it is usually not pos=
sible to find a closed-form solution; instead, an iterative numerical metho=
d must be used, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterativel=
y_reweighted_least_squares" title=3D"Iteratively reweighted least squares">=
iteratively reweighted least squares</a> (IRLS) or, more commonly these day=
s, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-Newton_method" title=3D=
"Quasi-Newton method">quasi-Newton method</a> such as the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-BFGS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"L-BFGS">L-BF=
GS method</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The interpretation of the <i>=CE=B2</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> parameter=
