<p>The logistic model has an equivalent formulation as a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent-variable_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Latent-variable model">latent-variable model</a>.  This formulation is =
common in the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_c=
hoice" title=3D"Discrete choice">discrete choice</a> models and makes it ea=
sier to extend to certain more complicated models with multiple, correlated=
 choices, as well as to compare logistic regression to the closely related =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probit_model" title=3D"Probit mode=
l">probit model</a>.
</p><p>Imagine that, for each trial <i>i</i>, there is a continuous <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Latent variable">latent variable</a> <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub><sup=
>*</sup> (i.e. an unobserved <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rando=
m_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable</a>) that is distribu=
ted as follows:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e Y_{i}^{\ast }=3D{\boldsymbol {\beta }}\cdot \mathbf {X} _{i}+\varepsilon =
_{i}\,}">
