<p>The choice of modeling the error variable specifically with a standard l=
ogistic distribution, rather than a general logistic distribution with the =
location and scale set to arbitrary values, seems restrictive, but in fact,=
 it is not.  It must be kept in mind that we can choose the regression coef=
ficients ourselves, and very often can use them to offset changes in the pa=
rameters of the error variable's distribution.  For example, a logistic err=
or-variable distribution with a non-zero location parameter <i>=CE=BC</i> (=
which sets the mean) is equivalent to a distribution with a zero location p=
arameter, where <i>=CE=BC</i> has been added to the intercept coefficient. =
 Both situations produce the same value for <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub><sup=
>*</sup> regardless of settings of explanatory variables.  Similarly, an ar=
bitrary scale parameter <i>s</i> is equivalent to setting the scale paramet=
er to 1 and then dividing all regression coefficients by <i>s</i>.  In the =
latter case, the resulting value of <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub><sup><i>*</i=
></sup> will be smaller by a factor of <i>s</i> than in the former case, fo=
r all sets of explanatory variables =E2=80=94 but critically, it will alway=
s remain on the same side of 0, and hence lead to the same <i>Y</i><sub><i>=
i</i></sub> choice.
</p><p>(This predicts that the irrelevancy of the scale parameter may not c=
arry over into more complex models where more than two choices are availabl=
e.)
</p><p>It turns out that this formulation is exactly equivalent to the prec=
eding one, phrased in terms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Generalized_linear_model" title=3D"Generalized linear model">generalized l=
inear model</a> and without any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La=
tent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latent variable">latent varia=
bles</a>.  This can be shown as follows, using the fact that the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulative_distribution_function" title=3D"C=
umulative distribution function">cumulative distribution function</a> (CDF)=
 of the standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_distribu=
tion" title=3D"Logistic distribution">logistic distribution</a> is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function" title=3D"Logistic f=
unction">logistic function</a>, which is the inverse of the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logit_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lo=
git function">logit function</a>, i.e.
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
