amp;{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This model has a separate latent variable and a separate set of regressi=
on coefficients for each possible outcome of the dependent variable.  The r=
eason for this separation is that it makes it easy to extend logistic regre=
ssion to multi-outcome categorical variables, as in the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_logit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mul=
tinomial logit">multinomial logit</a> model. In such a model, it is natural=
 to model each possible outcome using a different set of regression coeffic=
ients.  It is also possible to motivate each of the separate latent variabl=
es as the theoretical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utility" tit=
le=3D"Utility">utility</a> associated with making the associated choice, an=
d thus motivate logistic regression in terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Utility_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Utility theory=
">utility theory</a>. (In terms of utility theory, a rational actor always =
chooses the choice with the greatest associated utility.) This is the appro=
ach taken by economists when formulating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Discrete_choice" title=3D"Discrete choice">discrete choice</a> model=
s, because it both provides a theoretically strong foundation and facilitat=
es intuitions about the model, which in turn makes it easy to consider vari=
ous sorts of extensions. (See the example below.)
</p><p>The choice of the type-1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ex=
treme_value_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Extreme value dist=
ribution">extreme value distribution</a> seems fairly arbitrary, but it mak=
es the mathematics work out, and it may be possible to justify its use thro=
ugh <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_choice_theory" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational choice theory">rational choice theory</a=
>.
</p><p>It turns out that this model is equivalent to the previous model, al=
though this seems non-obvious, since there are now two sets of regression c=
oefficients and error variables, and the error variables have a different d=
istribution.  In fact, this model reduces directly to the previous one with=
 the following substitutions:
</p>
