l logit</a> model start out either by extending the "log-linear" formulatio=
n presented here or the two-way latent variable formulation presented above=
, since both clearly show the way that the model could be extended to multi=
-way outcomes.  In general, the presentation with latent variables is more =
common in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econometrics" title=3D"E=
conometrics">econometrics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Political_science" title=3D"Political science">political science</a>, where=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_choice" title=3D"Discret=
e choice">discrete choice</a> models and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Utility_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Utility theory">utili=
ty theory</a> reign, while the "log-linear" formulation here is more common=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Com=
puter science">computer science</a>, e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">machine learning</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_processing" ti=
tle=3D"Natural language processing">natural language processing</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_a_single-layer_perceptro=
