<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Model_fitting">Model fittin=
g</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_r=
egression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Model =
fitting"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Maximum_likelihood_estimati=
on_(MLE)"><span id=3D"Maximum_likelihood_estimation_.28MLE.29"></span>Maxim=
um likelihood estimation (MLE)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" =
title=3D"Edit section: Maximum likelihood estimation (MLE)"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The regression coefficients are usually estimated using <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_likelihood_estimation" title=3D"Maximum li=
kelihood estimation">maximum likelihood estimation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Menard_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
ogistic_regression#cite_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regre=
ssion#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Unlike linear regression with normally dist=
ributed residuals, it is not possible to find a closed-form expression for =
the coefficient values that maximize the likelihood function so an iterativ=
e process must be used instead; for example <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Newton%27s_method" title=3D"Newton's method">Newton's method</a>.=
 This process begins with a tentative solution, revises it slightly to see =
if it can be improved, and repeats this revision until no more improvement =
is made, at which point the process is said to have converged.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Menard_26-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In some instances, the model may not reach convergence. Non-converge=
nce of a model indicates that the coefficients are not meaningful because t=
he iterative process was unable to find appropriate solutions. A failure to=
 converge may occur for a number of reasons: having a large ratio of predic=
tors to cases, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multicollinearity" =
title=3D"Multicollinearity">multicollinearity</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_matrix" title=3D"Sparse matrix">sparseness</a>, or =
complete <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_(statistics)" =
title=3D"Separation (statistics)">separation</a>.
</p>
<ul><li>Having a large ratio of variables to cases results in an overly con=
servative Wald statistic (discussed below) and can lead to non-convergence.=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regularization_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Regularization (mathematics)">Regularized</a> logistic regression is =
specifically intended to be used in this situation.</li>
<li>Multicollinearity refers to unacceptably high correlations between pred=
ictors. As multicollinearity increases, coefficients remain unbiased but st=
andard errors increase and the likelihood of model convergence decreases.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Menard_26-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To de=
tect multicollinearity amongst the predictors, one can conduct a linear reg=
ression analysis with the predictors of interest for the sole purpose of ex=
amining the tolerance statistic <sup id=3D"cite_ref-Menard_26-3" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite=
_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  used to assess whether multicollinearity is u=
nacceptably high.</li>
<li>Sparseness in the data refers to having a large proportion of empty cel=
ls (cells with zero counts). Zero cell counts are particularly problematic =
with categorical predictors. With continuous predictors, the model can infe=
r values for the zero cell counts, but this is not the case with categorica=
l predictors. The model will not converge with zero cell counts for categor=
ical predictors because the natural logarithm of zero is an undefined value=
 so that the final solution to the model cannot be reached. To remedy this =
problem, researchers may collapse categories in a theoretically meaningful =
way or add a constant to all cells.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Menard_26-4" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression=
#cite_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Another numerical problem that may lead to a lack of convergence is com=
plete separation, which refers to the instance in which the predictors perf=
ectly predict the criterion&nbsp;=E2=80=93 all cases are accurately classif=
ied and the likelihood maximized with infinite coefficients. In such instan=
ces, one should re-examine the data, as there may be some kind of error.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Hosmer-2"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap=
;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" t=
itle=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"Why is there likely some k=
ind of error? How can this be remedied? (May 2017)">further explanation nee=
ded</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>One can also take semi-parametric or non-parametric approaches, e.g., v=
ia local-likelihood or nonparametric quasi-likelihood methods, which avoid =
assumptions of a parametric form for the index function and is robust to th=
e choice of the link function (e.g., probit or logit).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-s=
ciencedirect.com_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-sciencedirect.com-28"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></l=
i></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Iteratively_reweighted_leas=
t_squares_(IRLS)"><span id=3D"Iteratively_reweighted_least_squares_.28IRLS.=
29"></span>Iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS)</h3><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Iteratively reweighted lea=
st squares (IRLS)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>Binary logistic regression (<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
