<p>In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_statistics" title=
=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian statistics</a> context, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Prior distribution">prior distributions</a> are normally placed on the regr=
ession coefficients, for example in the form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gaussian_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gaussia=
n distribution">Gaussian distributions</a>.  There is no <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugate_prior" title=3D"Conjugate prior">conjugate=
 prior</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood_funct=
ion" title=3D"Likelihood function">likelihood function</a> in logistic regr=
ession.  When Bayesian inference was performed analytically, this made the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_distribution" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Posterior distribution">posterior distribution</a> dif=
ficult to calculate except in very low dimensions.  Now, though, automatic =
software such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenBUGS" title=
=3D"OpenBUGS">OpenBUGS</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Just_a=
nother_Gibbs_sampler" title=3D"Just another Gibbs sampler">JAGS</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PyMC" title=3D"PyMC">PyMC</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan_(software)" title=3D"Stan (software)=
">Stan</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing.jl" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Turing.jl">Turing.jl</a> allows these posteriors to b=
e computed using simulation, so lack of conjugacy is not a concern.  Howeve=
r, when the sample size or the number of parameters is large, full Bayesian=
 simulation can be slow, and people often use approximate methods such as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variational_Bayesian_methods" title=
=3D"Variational Bayesian methods">variational Bayesian methods</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expectation_propagation" title=3D"Expe=
ctation propagation">expectation propagation</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"&quot;Rule_of_ten&quot;"><s=
pan id=3D".22Rule_of_ten.22"></span>"Rule of ten"</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: &quot;Rule of ten&quot;"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_in_ten_rule" tit=
le=3D"One in ten rule">One in ten rule</a></div>
<p>Widely used, the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_in_ten_ru=
le" title=3D"One in ten rule">one in ten rule</a>", states that logistic re=
gression models give stable values for the explanatory variables if based o=
n a minimum of about 10 events per explanatory variable (EPV); where <i>eve=
nt</i> denotes the cases belonging to the less frequent category in the dep=
endent variable. Thus a study designed to use <span class=3D"mwe-math-eleme=
nt mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-=
mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998=
/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle k}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>k</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle k}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c3c9a2c7b599b37105512c5d570edc034056dd40" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.211ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle k}"=
></span> explanatory variables for an event (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Myocardial_infarction" title=3D"Myocardial infarction">myoc=
ardial infarction</a>) expected to occur in a proportion <span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle p}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>p</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle p}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/81eac1e205430d1f40810df36a0edffdc367af36" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:1.259ex; height:2.009ex;" al=
t=3D"{\displaystyle p}"></span> of participants in the study will require a=
 total of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cl=
ass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;=
"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displayst=
yle 10k/p}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>10</mn>
        <mi>k</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>p</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 10k/p}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3efcd5bca6797314284127bfc91e8a37f1810d53" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:5.868ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 10k=
/p}"></span> participants. However, there is considerable debate about the =
reliability of this rule, which is based on simulation studies and lacks a =
secure theoretical underpinning.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-30"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> According to some authors<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_no=
te-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> the rule is overly conservative in some circumstances, w=
ith the authors stating, "If we (somewhat subjectively) regard confidence i=
nterval coverage less than 93 percent, type I error greater than 7 percent,=
 or relative bias greater than 15 percent as problematic, our results indic=
ate that problems are fairly frequent with 2=E2=80=934 EPV, uncommon with 5=
=E2=80=939 EPV, and still observed with 10=E2=80=9316 EPV. The worst instan=
ces of each problem were not severe with 5=E2=80=939 EPV and usually compar=
able to those with 10=E2=80=9316 EPV".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_no=
te-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Others have found results that are not consistent with the above, us=
ing different criteria.  A useful criterion is whether the fitted model wil=
l be expected to achieve the same predictive discrimination in a new sample=
 as it appeared to achieve in the model development sample.  For that crite=
rion, 20 events per candidate variable may be required.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
plo14mod_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Logistic_regression#cite_note-plo14mod-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Also, one can argu=
e that 96 observations are needed only to estimate the model's intercept pr=
ecisely enough that the margin of error in predicted probabilities is =C2=
=B10.1 with a 0.95 confidence level.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rms_13-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cit=
e_note-rms-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Error_and_significance_of_f=
it">Error and significance of fit</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3=
5" title=3D"Edit section: Error and significance of fit"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Deviance_and_likelihood_rat=
io_test_=E2=94=80_a_simple_case"><span id=3D"Deviance_and_likelihood_ratio_=
test_.E2.94.80_a_simple_case"></span>Deviance and likelihood ratio test =E2=
=94=80 a simple case</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php=
?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D36" title=3D"E=
dit section: Deviance and likelihood ratio test =E2=94=80 a simple case"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>In any fitting procedure, the addition of another fitting parameter to a=
 model (e.g. the beta parameters in a logistic regression model) will almos=
t always improve the ability of the model to predict the measured outcomes.=
 This will be true even if the additional term has no predictive value, sin=
ce the model will simply be "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overf=
itting" title=3D"Overfitting">overfitting</a>" to the noise in the data.  T=
he question arises as to whether the improvement gained by the addition of =
another fitting parameter is significant enough to recommend the inclusion =
of the additional term, or whether the improvement is simply that which may=
 be expected from overfitting.
</p><p>In short, for logistic regression, a statistic known as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deviance_(statistics)" title=3D"Deviance =
(statistics)">deviance</a> is defined which is a measure of the error betwe=
en the logistic model fit and the outcome data. In the limit of a large num=
ber of data points, the deviance is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Chi-squared_distribution" title=3D"Chi-squared distribution">chi-squared<=
/a> distributed, which allows a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch=
i-squared_test" title=3D"Chi-squared test">chi-squared test</a> to be imple=
mented in order to determine the significance of the explanatory variables.
</p><p>Linear regression and logistic regression have many similarities. Fo=
r example, in simple linear regression, a set of <i>K</i> data points (<i>x=
<sub>k</sub></i>, <i>y<sub>k</sub></i>) are fitted to a proposed model func=
tion of the form <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><=
span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display=
: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\di=
splaystyle y=3Db_{0}+b_{1}x}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
