</p><p>We can imagine a case where the <i>y<sub>k</sub></i> data points are=
 randomly assigned to the various <i>x<sub>k</sub></i>, and then fitted usi=
ng the proposed model. Specifically, we can consider the fits of the propos=
ed model to every permutation of the <i>y<sub>k</sub></i> outcomes. It can =
be shown that the optimized error of any of these fits will never be less t=
han the optimum error of the null model, and that the difference between th=
ese minimum error will follow a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch=
i-squared_distribution" title=3D"Chi-squared distribution">chi-squared dist=
ribution</a>, with degrees of freedom equal those of the proposed model min=
us those of the null model which, in this case, will be <span class=3D"mwe-=
