<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Goodness_of_fit_summary">Go=
odness of fit summary</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"=
Edit section: Goodness of fit summary"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodness_of_fit" title=3D"Goodn=
ess of fit">Goodness of fit</a> in linear regression models is generally me=
asured using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_of_determ=
ination" title=3D"Coefficient of determination">R<sup>2</sup></a>. Since th=
is has no direct analog in logistic regression, various methods<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Greene_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Greene-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: ch.21">:=E2=80=8Ach.21=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup> including the following can be used instead.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Deviance_and_likelihood_rat=
io_tests">Deviance and likelihood ratio tests</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit section: Deviance and likelihood ratio tests">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>In linear regression analysis, one is concerned with partitioning varian=
ce via the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_sums_of_sq=
uares" title=3D"Partition of sums of squares">sum of squares</a> calculatio=
ns =E2=80=93 variance in the criterion is essentially divided into variance=
 accounted for by the predictors and residual variance. In logistic regress=
ion analysis, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deviance_(statistics=
)" title=3D"Deviance (statistics)">deviance</a> is used in lieu of a sum of=
 squares calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen_35-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Cohen=
-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Deviance is analogous to the sum of squares calculations i=
n linear regression<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-4" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Hosmer-2=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>  and is a measure of the lack of fit to the data in a logistic=
 regression model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Cohen-35"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> When a "saturated" model is available (a model with a theoreti=
cally perfect fit), deviance is calculated by comparing a given model with =
the saturated model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-5" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Hosmer-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>  This computation gives the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Likelihood-ratio_test" title=3D"Likelihood-ratio test">likelihood-r=
atio test</a>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Hosmer-2"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e D=3D-2\ln {\frac {\text{likelihood of the fitted model}}{\text{likelihood=
 of the saturated model}}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>D</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
