cket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Coefficient_significance">C=
oefficient significance</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D41" title=
=3D"Edit section: Coefficient significance"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After fitting the model, it is likely that researchers will want to exam=
ine the contribution of individual predictors. To do so, they will want to =
examine the regression coefficients. In linear regression, the regression c=
oefficients represent the change in the criterion for each unit change in t=
he predictor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen_35-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Cohen-35"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> In logistic regression, however, the regression coefficients repres=
ent the change in the logit for each unit change in the predictor. Given th=
at the logit is not intuitive, researchers are likely to focus on a predict=
or's effect on the exponential function of the regression coefficient =E2=
=80=93 the odds ratio (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logisti=
c_regression#Logistic_function,_odds,_odds_ratio,_and_logit">definition</a>=
). In linear regression, the significance of a regression coefficient is as=
sessed by computing a <i>t</i> test. In logistic regression, there are seve=
ral different tests designed to assess the significance of an individual pr=
edictor, most notably the likelihood ratio test and the Wald statistic.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Likelihood_ratio_test">Like=
lihood ratio test</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D42" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Likelihood ratio test"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood-ratio_test" titl=
e=3D"Likelihood-ratio test">likelihood-ratio test</a> discussed above to as=
sess model fit is also the recommended procedure to assess the contribution=
 of individual "predictors" to a given model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hosmer_2-9=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_reg=
ression#cite_note-Hosmer-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Menard_26-5" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regressio=
n#cite_note-Menard-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen_35-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression=
#cite_note-Cohen-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the case of a single predictor model, o=
ne simply compares the deviance of the predictor model with that of the nul=
l model on a chi-square distribution with a single degree of freedom. If th=
e predictor model has significantly smaller deviance (c.f. chi-square using=
 the difference in degrees of freedom of the two models), then one can conc=
lude that there is a significant association between the "predictor" and th=
e outcome. Although some common statistical packages (e.g. SPSS) do provide=
 likelihood ratio test statistics, without this computationally intensive t=
est it would be more difficult to assess the contribution of individual pre=
dictors in the multiple logistic regression case.<sup class=3D"noprint Inli=
ne-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Ci=
tation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sourc=
es. (October 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> To assess the con=
tribution of individual predictors one can enter the predictors hierarchica=
lly, comparing each new model with the previous to determine the contributi=
on of each predictor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen_35-8" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Cohen-=
35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> There is some debate among statisticians about the appropri=
ateness of so-called "stepwise" procedures.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Tem=
plate" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><span title=3D"Who says this? (Oc=
tober 2019)">weasel&nbsp;words</span></a></i>]</sup> The fear is that they =
may not preserve nominal statistical properties and may become misleading.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Wald_statistic">Wald statis=
tic</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic=
_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D43" title=3D"Edit section: Wald=
 statistic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Alternatively, when assessing the contribution of individual predictors =
in a given model, one may examine the significance of the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wald_test" title=3D"Wald test">Wald statistic</a>. =
The Wald statistic, analogous to the <i>t</i>-test in linear regression, is=
 used to assess the significance of coefficients. The Wald statistic is the=
 ratio of the square of the regression coefficient to the square of the sta=
ndard error of the coefficient and is asymptotically distributed as a chi-s=
quare distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Menard_26-6" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-Menard-=
26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e W_{j}=3D{\frac {\beta _{j}^{2}}{SE_{\beta _{j}}^{2}}}}">
