<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Discussion">Discussion</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regress=
ion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D45" title=3D"Edit section: Discussion">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>Like other forms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_=
analysis" title=3D"Regression analysis">regression analysis</a>, logistic r=
egression makes use of one or more predictor variables that may be either c=
ontinuous or categorical. Unlike ordinary linear regression, however, logis=
tic regression is used for predicting dependent variables that take <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_variable" title=3D"Categorica=
l variable">membership in one of a limited number of categories</a> (treati=
ng the dependent variable in the binomial case as the outcome of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_trial" title=3D"Bernoulli trial=
">Bernoulli trial</a>) rather than a continuous outcome. Given this differe=
nce, the assumptions of linear regression are violated. In particular, the =
residuals cannot be normally distributed. In addition, linear regression ma=
y make nonsensical predictions for a binary dependent variable. What is nee=
ded is a way to convert a binary variable into a continuous one that can ta=
ke on any real value (negative or positive). To do that, binomial logistic =
regression first calculates the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Od=
ds" title=3D"Odds">odds</a> of the event happening for different levels of =
each independent variable, and then takes its <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a> to create a contin=
uous criterion as a transformed version of the dependent variable. The loga=
rithm of the odds is the <span class=3D"texhtml"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Logit" title=3D"Logit">logit</a></span> of the probability, =
the <span class=3D"texhtml">logit</span> is defined as follows:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \operatorname {logit} p=3D\ln {\frac {p}{1-p}}\quad {\text{for =
}}0&lt;p&lt;1\,.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>logit</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>ln</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>p</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mn>1</mn>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mi>p</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"1em"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>for&nbsp;</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mn>0</mn>
