-align: -0.671ex; width:4.462ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle D_{=
\text{KL}}}"></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kullba=
ck%E2%80%93Leibler_divergence" title=3D"Kullback=E2=80=93Leibler divergence=
">Kullback=E2=80=93Leibler divergence</a>. This leads to the intuition that=
 by maximizing the log-likelihood of a model, you are minimizing the KL div=
ergence of your model from the maximal entropy distribution. Intuitively se=
arching for the model that makes the fewest assumptions in its parameters.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Comparison_with_linear_regr=
ession">Comparison with linear regression</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D47" title=3D"Edit section: Comparison with linear regression"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Logistic regression can be seen as a special case of the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model" title=3D"Generalized li=
near model">generalized linear model</a> and thus analogous to <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression" title=3D"Linear regression"=
>linear regression</a>. The model of logistic regression, however, is based=
 on quite different assumptions (about the relationship between the depende=
nt and independent variables) from those of linear regression. In particula=
r, the key differences between these two models can be seen in the followin=
g two features of logistic regression. First, the conditional distribution =
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe=
-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xm=
lns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle y\mid =
x}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=A3<!-- =E2=88=A3 --></mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle y\mid x}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9fed0364e2faac295815888b9762dcd1ea5f2fe6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:4.422ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle y\m=
id x}"></span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_dist=
ribution" title=3D"Bernoulli distribution">Bernoulli distribution</a> rathe=
r than a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_distribution" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gaussian distribution">Gaussian distribution</=
a>, because the dependent variable is binary. Second, the predicted values =
are probabilities and are therefore restricted to (0,1) through the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function" title=3D"Logistic func=
tion">logistic distribution function</a> because logistic regression predic=
ts the <b>probability</b> of particular outcomes rather than the outcomes t=
hemselves.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Alternatives">Alternatives<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_reg=
ression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D48" title=3D"Edit section: Alternat=
ives"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>A common alternative to the logistic model (logit model) is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probit_model" title=3D"Probit model">prob=
it model</a>, as the related names suggest. From the perspective of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model" title=3D"Genera=
lized linear model">generalized linear models</a>, these differ in the choi=
ce of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_function" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Link function">link function</a>: the logistic model uses=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logit_function" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Logit function">logit function</a> (inverse logistic func=
tion), while the probit model uses the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Probit_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Probit function">probi=
t function</a> (inverse <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_func=
tion" title=3D"Error function">error function</a>). Equivalently, in the la=
tent variable interpretations of these two methods, the first assumes a sta=
ndard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_distribution" title=
=3D"Logistic distribution">logistic distribution</a> of errors and the seco=
nd a standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution"=
 title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> of errors.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Logistic_regression#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function" title=3D"Sigmoid function">sigmoid func=
tions</a> or error distributions can be used instead.
</p><p>Logistic regression is an alternative to Fisher's 1936 method, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_discriminant_analysis" title=3D"=
Linear discriminant analysis">linear discriminant analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
gistic_regression#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  If the assumptions of linear d=
iscriminant analysis hold, the conditioning can be reversed to produce logi=
stic regression.  The converse is not true, however, because logistic regre=
ssion does not require the multivariate normal assumption of discriminant a=
nalysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The assumption of linear predictor effects can easily be relaxed usi=
ng techniques such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spline_(math=
ematics)" title=3D"Spline (mathematics)">spline functions</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-rms_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-rms-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regression&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D49" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A detailed history of the logistic regression is given in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFCramer2002">Cramer (2=
002)</a>. The logistic function was developed as a model of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_growth" title=3D"Population growth">po=
pulation growth</a> and named "logistic" by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pierre_Fran%C3%A7ois_Verhulst" title=3D"Pierre Fran=C3=A7ois Verh=
ulst">Pierre Fran=C3=A7ois Verhulst</a> in the 1830s and 1840s, under the g=
uidance of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolphe_Quetelet" title=
=3D"Adolphe Quetelet">Adolphe Quetelet</a>; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Logistic_function#History" title=3D"Logistic function">Logist=
ic function =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a> for details.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
ECramer20023=E2=80=935_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20023%E2%80%935-=
44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> In his earliest paper (1838), Verhulst did not specify how =
he fit the curves to the data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-45"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his mo=
re detailed paper (1845), Verhulst determined the three parameters of the m=
odel by making the curve pass through three observed points, which yielded =
poor predictions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-47"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20024_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20=
024-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The logistic function was independently developed in chemistry as a =
model of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autocatalysis" title=3D"A=
utocatalysis">autocatalysis</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ilhelm_Ostwald" title=3D"Wilhelm Ostwald">Wilhelm Ostwald</a>, 1883).<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20027_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20027=
-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> An autocatalytic reaction is one in which one of the produ=
cts is itself a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catalyst" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Catalyst">catalyst</a> for the same reaction, while =
the supply of one of the reactants is fixed. This naturally gives rise to t=
he logistic equation for the same reason as population growth: the reaction=
 is self-reinforcing but constrained.
</p><p>The logistic function was independently rediscovered as a model of p=
opulation growth in 1920 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raymon=
d_Pearl" title=3D"Raymond Pearl">Raymond Pearl</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lowell_Reed" title=3D"Lowell Reed">Lowell Reed</a>, pu=
blished as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CIT=
EREFPearlReed1920">Pearl &amp; Reed (1920)</a>, which led to its use in mod=
ern statistics. They were initially unaware of Verhulst's work and presumab=
ly learned about it from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L._Gustav=
e_du_Pasquier" title=3D"L. Gustave du Pasquier">L. Gustave du Pasquier</a>,=
 but they gave him little credit and did not adopt his terminology.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20026_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20026-=
50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Verhulst's priority was acknowledged and the term "logistic=
" revived by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udny_Yule" title=3D"U=
dny Yule">Udny Yule</a> in 1925 and has been followed since.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20026=E2=80=937_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer2002=
6%E2%80%937-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Pearl and Reed first applied the model to the p=
opulation of the United States, and also initially fitted the curve by maki=
ng it pass through three points; as with Verhulst, this again yielded poor =
results.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20025_52-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTN=
OTECramer20025-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1930s, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probit_mo=
del" title=3D"Probit model">probit model</a> was developed and systematized=
 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chester_Ittner_Bliss" title=3D=
"Chester Ittner Bliss">Chester Ittner Bliss</a>, who coined the term "probi=
t" in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFB=
liss1934">Bliss (1934)</a>, and by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/John_Gaddum" title=3D"John Gaddum">John Gaddum</a> in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFGaddum1933">Gaddum (1933)</=
a>, and the model fit by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_l=
ikelihood_estimation" title=3D"Maximum likelihood estimation">maximum likel=
ihood estimation</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_A._=
Fisher" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ronald A. Fisher">Ronald A. Fisher</=
a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFF=
isher1935">Fisher (1935)</a>, as an addendum to Bliss's work. The probit mo=
del was principally used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioass=
ay" title=3D"Bioassay">bioassay</a>, and had been preceded by earlier work =
dating to 1860; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probit_model#H=
istory" title=3D"Probit model">Probit model =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>. The pr=
obit model influenced the subsequent development of the logit model and the=
se models competed with each other.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20027=
=E2=80=939_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20027%E2%80%939-53"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The logistic model was likely first used as an alternative to the pr=
obit model in bioassay by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwin_Bi=
dwell_Wilson" title=3D"Edwin Bidwell Wilson">Edwin Bidwell Wilson</a> and h=
is student <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jane_Worcester" title=
=3D"Jane Worcester">Jane Worcester</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFWilsonWorcester1943">Wilson &amp; Worces=
ter (1943)</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer20029_54-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_not=
e-FOOTNOTECramer20029-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the development of the logis=
tic model as a general alternative to the probit model was principally due =
to the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Berkson" tit=
le=3D"Joseph Berkson">Joseph Berkson</a> over many decades, beginning in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFBerkson19=
44">Berkson (1944)</a>, where he coined "logit", by analogy with "probit", =
and continuing through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_re=
gression#CITEREFBerkson1951">Berkson (1951)</a> and following years.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The logit model was initia=
lly dismissed as inferior to the probit model, but "gradually achieved an e=
qual footing with the probit",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer200211_56-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_reg=
ression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer200211-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> particularly between=
 1960 and 1970. By 1970, the logit model achieved parity with the probit mo=
del in use in statistics journals and thereafter surpassed it. This relativ=
e popularity was due to the adoption of the logit outside of bioassay, rath=
er than displacing the probit within bioassay, and its informal use in prac=
tice; the logit's popularity is credited to the logit model's computational=
 simplicity, mathematical properties, and generality, allowing its use in v=
aried fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer200210=E2=80=9311_3-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer200210%E2%80%9311-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Various refinements occurred during that time, notably by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Cox_(statistician)" title=3D"David Cox=
 (statistician)">David Cox</a>, as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFCox1958">Cox (1958)</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
wal67est_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Logistic_regression#cite_note-wal67est-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The multinomial logit model was introduced independently in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#CITEREFCox1966">Cox (=
1966)</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#=
CITEREFTheil1969">Theil (1969)</a>, which greatly increased the scope of ap=
plication and the popularity of the logit model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
ECramer200213_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer200213-57"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In=
 1973 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_McFadden" title=3D"Da=
niel McFadden">Daniel McFadden</a> linked the multinomial logit to the theo=
ry of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_choice" title=3D"Di=
screte choice">discrete choice</a>, specifically <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Luce%27s_choice_axiom" title=3D"Luce's choice axiom">Luce's =
choice axiom</a>, showing that the multinomial logit followed from the assu=
mption of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independence_of_irreleva=
nt_alternatives" title=3D"Independence of irrelevant alternatives">independ=
ence of irrelevant alternatives</a> and interpreting odds of alternatives a=
s relative preferences;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-58"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> this gave a theoretical foundation for the logistic regression.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECramer200213_57-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression#cite_note-FOOTNOTECramer20021=
3-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions">Extensions</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLogistic_regress=
ion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D50" title=3D"Edit section: Extensions">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>There are large numbers of extensions:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_logistic_regre=
ssion" title=3D"Multinomial logistic regression">Multinomial logistic regre=
ssion</a> (or <b>multinomial logit</b>) handles the case of a multi-way <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_variable" title=3D"Catego=
rical variable">categorical</a> dependent variable (with unordered values, =
also called "classification").  The general case of having dependent variab=
les with more than two values is termed <i>polytomous regression</i>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordered_logistic_regression" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ordered logistic regression">Ordered logistic=
 regression</a> (or <b>ordered logit</b>) handles <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Levels_of_measurement#Ordinal_measurement" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Levels of measurement">ordinal</a> dependent variables (orde=
red values).</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mixed_logit" title=3D"Mixed lo=
git">Mixed logit</a> is an extension of multinomial logit that allows for c=
orrelations among the choices of the dependent variable.</li>
<li>An extension of the logistic model to sets of interdependent variables =
is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_random_field" t=
itle=3D"Conditional random field">conditional random field</a>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_logistic_regressio=
n" title=3D"Conditional logistic regression">Conditional logistic regressio=
n</a> handles <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matching_(statistics=
)" title=3D"Matching (statistics)">matched</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Stratification_(clinical_trials)" title=3D"Stratification (=
clinical trials)">stratified</a> data when the strata are small. It is most=
ly used in the analysis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observa=
